<paragraph blockId="5.[163,1071,1263,1487]" lastBlockId="7.[163,1070,204,372]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="1226" pageId="5" pageNumber="1224">
D e s c r i p t i o n: Length of body 
<quantity box="[551,632,1348,1369]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.8" pageId="5" pageNumber="1224" unit="mm" value="4.8">4.8 mm</quantity>
; from anterior margin of head to posterior margin of elytra: 
<quantity box="[345,427,1377,1399]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.6" pageId="5" pageNumber="1224" unit="mm" value="2.6">2.6 mm</quantity>
. Body shiny, slender. Reddish brown light; antennae and legs yellowish pale. Head ovoid, narrow, slightly dilated forward, with rounded sides from the eyes to the neck, and obsolete posterior angles. Eyes medium-sized and protruding. Surface of head with very few punctures. Pronotum sub-rectangular, more or less as long as head, narrower than it, with very oblique anterior margins, obsolete anterior angles and a little sinuate sides. Surface with dorsal series of 5-6 superficial, spaced punctures and lateral series of 2 posterior punctures. Elytra sub-rectangular, not dilated posteriad, longer and wider than pronotum, with rounded humeral angles. Surface with three series of very fine punctures, one juxtasutural, one median and one lateral. Abdomen with traces of fine, transverse micro-striation and fine, very sparse punctation.
</paragraph>
<caption pageId="6" pageNumber="1225" startId="6.[163,203,1491,1513]" targetBox="[265,1007,217,1471]" targetPageId="6">
<paragraph blockId="6.[163,1070,1491,1559]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1225">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[163,267,1491,1513]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1225">Figs 10-15</emphasis>
: Tergite and sternite of the male genital segment and aedeagus (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[908,961,1491,1512]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1225">10-12</emphasis>
) of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bordoni" authorityYear="2017" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Denon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="1225" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="silvestris" status="nov.sp.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="1225">Denon silvestris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[252,321,1514,1535]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1225" rank="species">nov.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, Male genital segment, sternite of the same and aedeagus (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[887,939,1514,1535]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1225">13-15</emphasis>
) of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bordoni" authorityYear="2017" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Indolinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="1225" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inermis" status="nov.sp.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="1225">Indolinus inermis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[237,303,1537,1558]" pageId="6" pageNumber="1225" rank="species">nov.sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(scale bar: 0.1 mm).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="7.[163,1070,388,498]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">
Male genital segment long and narrow (
<figureCitation box="[568,643,388,410]" captionStart="Figs 10-15" captionStartId="6.[163,203,1491,1513]" captionTargetBox="[265,1007,217,1471]" captionTargetId="figure-44@6.[218,1015,196,1481]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 10-15: Tergite and sternite of the male genital segment and aedeagus (10-12) of Denon silvestris nov.sp., Male genital segment, sternite of the same and aedeagus (13-15) of Indolinus inermis nov.sp. (scale bar: 0.1 mm)." pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
); sternite of the same as in 
<figureCitation box="[921,994,388,410]" captionStart="Figs 10-15" captionStartId="6.[163,203,1491,1513]" captionTargetBox="[265,1007,217,1471]" captionTargetId="figure-44@6.[218,1015,196,1481]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 10-15: Tergite and sternite of the male genital segment and aedeagus (10-12) of Denon silvestris nov.sp., Male genital segment, sternite of the same and aedeagus (13-15) of Indolinus inermis nov.sp. (scale bar: 0.1 mm)." pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
, with 2 long setae on the lateral, posterior lobules. Aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[744,822,417,439]" captionStart="Figs 10-15" captionStartId="6.[163,203,1491,1513]" captionTargetBox="[265,1007,217,1471]" captionTargetId="figure-44@6.[218,1015,196,1481]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 10-15: Tergite and sternite of the male genital segment and aedeagus (10-12) of Denon silvestris nov.sp., Male genital segment, sternite of the same and aedeagus (13-15) of Indolinus inermis nov.sp. (scale bar: 0.1 mm)." pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
) 
<quantity box="[840,921,417,438]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226" unit="mm" value="1.3">1.3 mm</quantity>
long, oblong, narrow, with long, peculaiar parameres; inner sac long, covered in the distal portion with two parallel series of pale scales.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[163,1070,513,564]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">
E t y m o l o g y: The specific epithet is the Latin 
<emphasis box="[706,811,514,535]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">inermis- e</emphasis>
(unarmed) in relation to the few, pale scales of the inner sac.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[163,896,580,602]" box="[163,896,580,602]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">
D i s t r i b u t i o n: The species is known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[763,807,580,601]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">type</typeStatus>
locality.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[163,1070,616,786]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">
R e m a r k s: When the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="(BORDONI, 2002)" baseAuthorityName="BORDONI" baseAuthorityYear="2002" box="[502,791,616,639]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Indolinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[502,598,617,638]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">Indolinus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="BORDONI A" box="[615,784,616,639]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226" refId="ref4604" refString="BORDONI A. (2002): Xantholinini della Regione Orientale (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae). Classificazione, filogenesi e revisione tassonomica. - Memorie del Museo regionale di Scienze naturali Torino 33: 998 pp." type="book" year="2002">BORDONI, 2002</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
was described, the known species were only three (
<taxonomicName authority="(COIFFAIT, 1984)" baseAuthorityName="COIFFAIT" baseAuthorityYear="1984" box="[450,849,645,669]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Indolinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mitomorphoides">
<emphasis box="[450,645,646,668]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">I. mitomorphoides</emphasis>
(COIFFAIT, 1984)
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[929,984,646,668]" name="India" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">India</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1003,1066,646,668]" name="Nepal" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">Nepal</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[163,264,676,697]" name="Myanmar" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">Myanmar</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[275,365,676,698]" name="Thailand" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">Thailand</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[415,467,676,697]" name="Laos" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">Laos</collectingCountry>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="BORDONI, 2002" authorityName="BORDONI" authorityYear="2002" box="[478,767,674,697]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Indolinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="formosae">
<emphasis box="[478,594,676,697]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">I. formosae</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="BORDONI A" box="[601,767,674,697]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226" refId="ref4604" refString="BORDONI A. (2002): Xantholinini della Regione Orientale (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae). Classificazione, filogenesi e revisione tassonomica. - Memorie del Museo regionale di Scienze naturali Torino 33: 998 pp." type="book" year="2002">BORDONI, 2002</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[830,906,676,698]" name="Taiwan" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="BORDONI, 2002" authorityName="BORDONI" authorityYear="2002" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Indolinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sculptilis">
<emphasis box="[956,1070,676,697]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">I. sculptilis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="BORDONI A" box="[164,328,704,727]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226" refId="ref4604" refString="BORDONI A. (2002): Xantholinini della Regione Orientale (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae). Classificazione, filogenesi e revisione tassonomica. - Memorie del Museo regionale di Scienze naturali Torino 33: 998 pp." type="book" year="2002">BORDONI, 2002</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[391,514,705,726]" name="Hong Kong" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">Hong Kong</collectingCountry>
. Further researchs has shown that this genus is present in the Oriental Region with other species, though not common and usually represented by isolated specimens.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[163,1071,800,882]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">
Also known are 
<emphasis box="[339,484,802,823]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">I. vietnamicus</emphasis>
BORDONI, 2012 from 
<collectingCountry box="[729,819,801,823]" name="Vietnam" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="BORDONI, 2013 b" authorityName="BORDONI" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Indolinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laosianus">
<emphasis box="[832,953,801,823]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">I. laosianus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="BORDONI A" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226" pagination="191 - 198" refId="ref4881" refString="BORDONI A. (2013 b): New data on the Xanthiolnini from the Oriental Region. 32. New species and new records of North Laos in the collection Hayashi (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). - Japanese Journal of systematic Entomology 19 (2): 191 - 198." type="journal article" year="2013">BORDONI, 2013b</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[295,344,831,852]" name="Laos" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">Laos</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[400,487,830,852]" name="Vietnam" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="BORDONI, 2013 a" authorityName="BORDONI" authorityYear="2013" box="[543,833,829,852]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Indolinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leigong">
<emphasis box="[543,644,830,852]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">I. leigong</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="BORDONI A" box="[654,833,829,852]" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226" pagination="1745 - 1797" refId="ref4830" refString="BORDONI A. (2013 a): New data on the Xantholinini from China. 24. New genus, new species and new records of the Shanghai Normal University collection (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). - Linzer biologische Beitrage 45 (2): 1745 - 1797." type="journal article" year="2013">BORDONI, 2013a</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[902,963,830,852]" name="China" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">China</collectingCountry>
(Guizou). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bordoni" authorityYear="2017" box="[163,341,860,881]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Indolinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inermis">
<emphasis box="[163,341,860,881]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="1226">Indolinus inermis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is therefore the seventh known species of this genus.
</paragraph>
